es throughout on early jazz and swing but includes its re-creation—reinvention—in the 1950s. Along the way, he pays tribute to forgotten traditions such as black musical theater, white show bands, and French wartime swing. Paris Blues provides a nuanced account of the French reception of African Americans and their music and contributes greatly to a growing literature on jazz, race, and nation in France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican American jazz musicianszFrance. 0aAfrican Americans in the performing artszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican Americans in the performing artszFrancexHistoryy20thcentury. 0aJazzzFrancey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusical filmszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aMusical theaterzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  amusic history, french popular culture france, jazz age, criticism, 20th century, improvisation, paris, african american musicians, racism, race relations, racial issues, traditional icons, josephine baker, django reinhardt, sidney bechet, forgotten traditions, musical theater, white show bands, wartime swing, performing arts, revue negre.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226138954423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226138954/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles